WEBVTT

00:00:19.760 --> 00:00:21.930
WE'VE COME TO A CARIBBEAN ISLAND

00:00:21.930 --> 00:00:24.200
WHOSE ONLY INHABITANTS
ARE MONKEYS

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:28.230
TO ASK THE QUESTION: WHAT CAN
THEY TEACH US ABOUT OURSELVES?

00:00:29.230 --> 00:00:31.930
<i>CAN WE FIND THE ROOTS
 OF HUMAN MORALITY</i>

00:00:31.930 --> 00:00:34.060
<i>IN HOW CHIMPANZEES SHARE?</i>

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:36.830
<i>DO CHIMPS USE TOOLS...</i>

00:00:36.830 --> 00:00:37.900
YOU WANT A STICK?

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:39.900
<i>THE SAME WAY WE DO?</i>

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:44.260
<i>WHAT'S THE LINK
 BETWEEN THIS ODD PRIMATE</i>

00:00:44.260 --> 00:00:46.060
<i>AND A SPECIAL HUMAN SKILL?</i>

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:49.530
IT MAKES HER SMILE.

00:00:49.530 --> 00:00:52.730
<i>AND WE'LL FIND OUT HOW
 TO BEHAVE IN POLITE SOCIETY.</i>

00:00:53.730 --> 00:00:55.160
I'M ALAN ALDA.

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.560
JOIN ME AND MY NEW FRIENDS
FOR "PRIME TIME PRIMATES."

00:01:10.400 --> 00:01:12.800
[Captioning sponsored by GTE]

00:01:22.900 --> 00:01:26.930
PRESENTATION OF
<i> SCIENTIFIC AMERICAN FRONTIERS</i>

00:01:26.930 --> 00:01:31.060
IS MADE POSSIBLE BY A GRANT
FROM GTE CORPORATION.

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:35.230
AT GTE, IT'S AMAZING
WHAT WE CAN DO TOGETHER.

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:44.560
Alda:
THIS ISLAND OFF
THE COAST OF PUERTO RICO

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:48.200
IS A PRESERVE FOR MACAQUE
MONKEYS ORIGINALLY FROM INDIA.

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:52.430
MONKEYS HERE LIVE PRETTY MUCH AS
THEY WOULD IF WE WEREN'T AROUND.

00:01:57.830 --> 00:02:00.200
IT'S A GREAT PLACE
FOR MONKEY WATCHING.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:05.500
(<i> screeching</i> )

00:02:10.460 --> 00:02:13.460
MONKEY WATCHING IS FASCINATING
FOR TWO REASONS--

00:02:13.460 --> 00:02:14.730
HOW LIKE US THEY ARE

00:02:14.730 --> 00:02:16.630
AND HOW<i> NOT</i> LIKE US THEY ARE.

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:19.630
THE BIG DIFFERENCE, OF COURSE,
IS IN OUR HEADS.

00:02:19.630 --> 00:02:23.060
PEOPLE ARE CAPABLE OF LANGUAGE,
MATHEMATICS, CULTURE

00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:24.730
COMPLEX SOCIAL STRUCTURES

00:02:24.730 --> 00:02:26.300
WONDERS THAT SEEM TO US

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:29.200
TO BE SO FAR ABOVE
THE ABILITIES OF MONKEYS

00:02:29.200 --> 00:02:31.430
THAT THEY MUST BE
UNIQUELY HUMAN.

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:32.900
BUT ARE THEY?

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:36.300
THAT'S THE QUESTION WE'LL BE
ASKING FOR THE NEXT HOUR.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:37.960
HOW MUCH OF<i> US</i> IS IN<i> THEM?</i>

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:39.900
AND HOW MUCH OF<i> THEM</i> IS IN<i> US?</i>

00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:44.330
OUR FIRST STORY IS ABOUT WHAT
THESE DAYS IS A VERY HOT TOPIC--

00:02:45.730 --> 00:02:47.730
AGGRESSION.

00:02:52.730 --> 00:02:56.400
MACAQUES-- RHESUS MONKEYS--
SPEND MUCH OF THEIR TIME

00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:58.160
HANGING OUT IN LARGE GROUPS.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:00.360
MOSTLY, THEY GET ALONG
JUST FINE

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:03.400
AND ARGUMENTS ONLY RARELY
TURN VIOLENT ENOUGH

00:03:03.400 --> 00:03:05.330
FOR SOMEONE TO GET HURT.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:11.030
AND WHEN THINGS DO GET
A LITTLE TOO STRESSFUL

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:13.860
THE MONKEYS HAVE PLENTY OF ROOM
ON THE ISLAND

00:03:13.860 --> 00:03:15.630
TO GET AWAY FROM IT ALL.

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:20.800
BUT WHAT IF THEY LIVED
IN MORE CROWDED CONDITIONS?

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:22.760
THESE MONKEYS AREN'T
ON AN ISLAND.

00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:24.400
THEY'RE IN A LARGE ENCLOSURE

00:03:24.400 --> 00:03:26.730
AT THE YERKES PRIMATE CENTER
IN ATLANTA.

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:30.160
HOW THEY COPE WITH CROWDING HERE
MAY HELP US UNDERSTAND

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:33.700
HOW THEIR FELLOW PRIMATES,
PEOPLE, COPE WITH THE STRESS

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:35.760
OF LIVING IN THE CROWDED CITIES.

00:03:36.900 --> 00:03:40.600
IT MAY LOOK AS THOUGH THE
MONKEYS HERE HAVE PLENTY OF ROOM

00:03:40.600 --> 00:03:42.860
BUT THEY'RE 500 TIMES
MORE CROWDED

00:03:42.860 --> 00:03:44.730
THAN THEY ARE ON THE ISLAND.

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:54.100
THEY'RE PART OF
A LONG-TERM EXPERIMENT

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:55.800
ON CROWDING IN MONKEYS

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:59.630
INSPIRED BY THE IDEAS OF YERKES
PRIMATOLOGIST FRANS DE WAAL.

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:03.300
HOW LONG HAVE PEOPLE BEEN
STUDYING CROWDING IN ANIMALS?

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:04.600
PROBABLY VERY LONG.

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:07.230
THE MOST INFLUENTIAL STUDY
CAME OUT IN THE '60s

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:09.230
WHERE SOMEONE DID
A STUDY ON RATS.

00:04:09.230 --> 00:04:10.800
RATS LIVED IN A SMALL ROOM

00:04:10.800 --> 00:04:13.900
AND AS IT GOT MORE CROWDED,
THE MORE THEY MULTIPLIED

00:04:13.900 --> 00:04:15.860
AND THEY BECAME
VERY AGGRESSIVE.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.930
THEY EVEN KILLED
AND ATE EACH OTHER.

00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:21.330
Alda:
IT'S UNUSUAL HERE AT YERKES

00:04:21.330 --> 00:04:24.930
FOR THE MONKEYS TO GET PACKED
TOGETHER THE WAY THE RATS WERE

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:26.330
BUT EVERY NOW AND THEN

00:04:26.330 --> 00:04:29.400
THEY HAVE TO BE ROUNDED UP
FOR ROUTINE MEDICAL CARE.

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:32.230
THEY'RE USED TO THE OPERATION

00:04:32.230 --> 00:04:34.460
AND THEY HEAD
FOR THEIR INDOOR CAGE

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:36.530
AS SOON AS THEIR KEEPERS APPEAR.

00:04:46.900 --> 00:04:49.660
ONCE INSIDE, THEY'RE ANYTHING
BUT AGGRESSIVE.

00:04:49.660 --> 00:04:51.860
IN FACT, THEIR BEHAVIOR
REMINDED ME

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:55.700
OF THE WAY WE HUMANS COPE WITH
BEING TIGHTLY PACKED TOGETHER.

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:58.260
Alda:
WHEN YOU CROWD PEOPLE
IN AN ELEVATOR

00:04:58.260 --> 00:05:00.260
YOU DON'T TEND
TO GET AGGRESSION

00:05:00.260 --> 00:05:03.000
YOU TEND TO GET RITUALIZED
POLITE BEHAVIOR.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.460
PEOPLE DON'T EVEN
LOOK AT ONE ANOTHER.

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:07.200
YEAH, THEY AVOID
INTERACTION

00:05:07.200 --> 00:05:10.100
AND SO THEY AVOID ANYTHING
THAT MAY CAUSE PROBLEMS

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:12.160
BECAUSE IT'S A VERY
CROWDED SPACE.

00:05:12.160 --> 00:05:14.160
AND IF YOU DO
WITH RHESUS MONKEYS

00:05:14.160 --> 00:05:16.030
AN ACUTE CROWDING EXPERIMENT--

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:19.260
SORT OF THE ELEVATOR EFFECT--
YOU GET SIMILAR BEHAVIOR.

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:22.460
THEY MAY STAY NEXT TO EACH
OTHER, BUT THEY DON'T MOVE

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:24.560
AND THEY DON'T INTERACT
VERY MUCH.

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:27.300
Alda:
SO WHEN WE'RE REALLY
PACKED TOGETHER

00:05:27.300 --> 00:05:30.400
PEOPLE AND MONKEYS
SEEM TO COPE IN THE SAME WAY

00:05:30.400 --> 00:05:31.860
BY BEING VERY CAREFUL.

00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:33.830
BUT WHAT ABOUT EVERYDAY LIFE?

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:40.530
MONKEY SOCIETY IS BASED
ON A STRICT HIERARCHY

00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:42.900
IN WHICH EVERYONE KNOWS
HIS OR HER PLACE.

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.000
IN THIS MODERATELY
CROWDED ENCLOSURE

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.430
ONE IMPORTANT WAY TO AVOID
CONFLICT IS BY GRINNING A LOT--

00:05:48.430 --> 00:05:51.600
MORE SCIENTIFICALLY CALLED
"THE BARED TEETH RESPONSE."

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:54.130
De Waal:
THAT'S A BEHAVIOR
THAT GOES UP DRAMATICALLY

00:05:54.130 --> 00:05:55.900
UNDER MORE CROWDED
CONDITIONS

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:58.800
AS IF THE SUBORDINATES ARE
TELLING THE DOMINANTS

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.300
"I'M STILL SUBORDINATE
IN THE HIERARCHY

00:06:01.300 --> 00:06:03.600
SO YOU DON'T NEED
TO ATTACK ME."

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:06.830
ARE THERE SOME MONKEYS
WHERE BARING THE TEETH

00:06:06.830 --> 00:06:08.630
IS A SIGN OF AGGRESSION?

00:06:08.630 --> 00:06:10.930
YOU CAN SHOW YOUR
TEETH IN TWO WAYS.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:13.160
IF A RHESUS MONKEY
OPENS THE MOUTH

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:14.560
AND STARES AT SOMEONE

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:16.160
THAT'S A THREAT.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.900
BUT BARING THE TEETH
IN A SMILE TYPE OF WAY

00:06:18.900 --> 00:06:20.400
IS A SUBMISSIVE GESTURE.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:23.200
IN THE APES SUCH AS
CHIMPANZEES AND IN HUMANS

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.130
IT HAS GOT AN AFFILIATIVE
AND FRIENDLY COMPONENT

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:28.560
BUT STILL NERVOUSNESS
IS OFTEN INVOLVED

00:06:28.560 --> 00:06:30.430
AND IF SOMEONE SMILES
TOO MUCH

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:32.400
WE SAY THAT'S
A NERVOUS PERSON.

00:06:32.400 --> 00:06:33.730
RIGHT.

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:36.330
I'M A LITTLE NERVOUS

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:39.030
ABOUT GETTING SCRATCHED
AND BITTEN LATER.

00:06:39.030 --> 00:06:43.630
Alda:
PETER JUDGE IS IN CHARGE
OF THE CROWDING STUDIES.

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:46.500
HERE'S A TYPICAL INCIDENT

00:06:46.500 --> 00:06:49.700
IN THE LONG HOURS
HE SPENDS MONKEY WATCHING.

00:06:49.700 --> 00:06:52.000
THIS BABY IS JUST
A FEW WEEKS OLD

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.100
AND A POPULAR PLAYMATE
FOR THE OTHER MONKEYS.

00:06:55.100 --> 00:06:57.600
THE MOTHER, NAMED ALLIE

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:01.930
IS CONSTANTLY FENDING OFF
UNWANTED INVITATIONS.

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:03.330
(<i> screeching</i> )

00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:06.500
SUDDENLY, A YOUNG MONKEY
CALLED D.J. GETS TOO ROUGH.

00:07:06.500 --> 00:07:08.600
ALLIE THREAT D.J.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:11.530
Alda:
BUT MOMENTS LATER,
D.J. APPROACHES ALLIE

00:07:11.530 --> 00:07:13.630
AND THE TWO MONKEYS MAKE UP.

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:15.900
D.J. SIT
PROXIMITY ALLIE.

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:18.230
D.J. GROOM ALLIE.

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:22.300
Alda:
GROOMING EACH OTHER IS THE
MONKEY'S MAIN WAY OF RELAXING

00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:24.300
AND HAVING A GOOD TIME TOGETHER.

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:25.800
WHAT PETER JUDGE FOUND

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:29.430
IS THAT IN THE POTENTIALLY
EXPLOSIVE CONDITIONS OF CROWDING

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:33.130
MONKEYS DO A LOT MORE TO KEEP
THE PEACE BETWEEN EACH OTHER

00:07:33.130 --> 00:07:35.860
THAN THEY DO WHEN
THEY HAVE ROOM TO SPARE.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:38.460
Judge:
IF YOU LOOK AT
AGGRESSIVE BEHAVIOR

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:41.200
SOME AGGRESSION GOES UP,
AND SOME DOESN'T.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:43.200
IF YOU LOOK AT
FRIENDLY BEHAVIOR

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:46.500
ALMOST EVERY CATEGORY
OF FRIENDLY BEHAVIOR INCREASES.

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:48.330
IF IN A CONDITION LIKE THAT

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.860
WHERE YOU'RE ALWAYS CLOSE
TO YOUR POTENTIAL AGGRESSOR

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:53.300
IT'S WORTH YOUR WHILE

00:07:53.300 --> 00:07:57.730
TO RESTORE THE RELATIONSHIP
AND RESOLVE THE CONFLICT.

00:07:57.730 --> 00:08:02.100
Alda:
RHESUS MONKEYS HAVE BEEN OFF ON
THEIR OWN EVOLUTIONARY PATHWAY

00:08:02.100 --> 00:08:04.660
SEPARATE FROM THE ONE
THAT LED TO HUMANS

00:08:04.660 --> 00:08:06.960
FOR SOMETHING LIKE
30 MILLION YEARS.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:08.700
MORE CLOSELY RELATED TO US--

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:11.760
SEPARATED BY ONLY SIX MILLION
YEARS OF EVOLUTION--

00:08:11.760 --> 00:08:13.300
ARE CHIMPANZEES.

00:08:15.630 --> 00:08:17.460
IT WAS WATCHING CHIMPS

00:08:17.460 --> 00:08:20.860
THAT FIRST CONVINCED
FRANS DE WAAL 20 YEARS AGO

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:23.360
THAT THE HIGHER PRIMATES
ALL SHARE

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:26.400
A DEEPLY-ROOTED INSTINCT
FOR MAKING PEACE.

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:29.130
THIS GROUP OF 19 CHIMPANZEES

00:08:29.130 --> 00:08:31.230
LIVING BELOW FRANS' OFFICE
AT YERKES

00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:33.960
INCLUDED JIMOH, THE ALPHA MALE
OR GROUP LEADER

00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:38.130
AND PEONY, THE DOMINANT FEMALE,
HERE WITH HER DAUGHTER.

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:42.100
THE ADOLESCENT MALES
IN THE GROUP

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:44.160
OFTEN ACT LIKE ADOLESCENTS.

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:46.630
BUT THE FIGHTS
RARELY GET SERIOUS

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:48.760
AND AS WITH THE RHESUS MONKEYS

00:08:48.760 --> 00:08:51.900
THEY USUALLY END
IN FRIENDLY RECONCILIATIONS

00:08:51.900 --> 00:08:55.400
THIS ONE INVOLVING
TICKLING AND LAUGHTER.

00:08:58.660 --> 00:09:02.300
NOW WE WILL THROW THEM
IN ONE AT A TIME.

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:06.300
Alda:
FRANS RECENTLY BEGAN
SOME EXPERIMENTS WITH HIS CHIMPS

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:09.700
THAT ARE CONVINCING HIM
THAT NOT ONLY PEACEMAKING

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:13.100
BUT EVEN SUCH SUPPOSEDLY
HUMAN TRAITS AS MORALITY

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:16.800
HAVE BIOLOGICAL ROOTS
THAT WE SHARE WITH CHIMPANZEES.

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:21.800
THESE BUNDLES OF LEAVES
ARE A TREAT FOR THE CHIMPS

00:09:21.800 --> 00:09:24.560
AN ADDITION TO
THEIR REGULAR DIET.

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:26.960
De Waal:
THAT'S A JUVENILE
WHO TOOK IT

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:29.730
AND THE ALPHA MALE
TAKES IT OVER FROM HIM.

00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:32.400
Alda:
MOST OF THE CHIMPS GATHER
AROUND A BUNDLE

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:34.260
AND PEACEFULLY SHARE THE LEAVES.

00:09:34.260 --> 00:09:36.000
BUT THE BUNDLE RIGHT BELOW US

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.430
WAS TAKEN BY A YOUNG FEMALE
CALLED GEORGIA

00:09:38.430 --> 00:09:40.400
WHO IS MUCH LESS WILLING
TO SHARE.

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:41.700
IS GEORGIA
STINGY

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:43.830
BECAUSE SHE HASN'T LEARNED
TO SHARE

00:09:43.830 --> 00:09:45.560
OR IS SHE NATURALLY STINGY?

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:47.360
IN HUMAN TERMS,
YOU WOULD SAY

00:09:47.360 --> 00:09:50.530
SHE DOESN'T HAVE THE CONFIDENCE
AND THE POSITION YET

00:09:50.530 --> 00:09:52.230
TO BE GENEROUS WITH OTHERS.

00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:54.930
SHE'S STILL VERY MUCH
IN A COMPETITIVE MODE

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:57.230
LIKE "HOW MUCH
CAN I GET MYSELF?"

00:09:57.230 --> 00:10:01.730
Alda:
GEORGIA SAT WITH HER BACK TO US
FIRMLY MONOPOLIZING HER BUNDLE.

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:06.700
WE COLLECT THOUSANDS
OF FOOD TRANSFERS

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:08.060
BETWEEN INDIVIDUALS.

00:10:08.060 --> 00:10:10.000
AMONG ADULTS,
IT'S RECIPROCAL--

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.700
IF I SHARE WITH YOU,
YOU WILL SHARE WITH ME.

00:10:12.700 --> 00:10:14.760
JUVENILES ARE TOTALLY
OUT OF THIS.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:18.060
JUVENILES WORK ON
A STEALING OPERATION.

00:10:19.060 --> 00:10:21.730
Alda:
GEORGIA'S TACTIC
OF STEALING BACKFIRES

00:10:21.730 --> 00:10:25.060
AS ANOTHER JUVENILE STEALS
THE WHOLE BUNDLE FROM HER.

00:10:25.060 --> 00:10:27.730
THAT'S A TYPICAL
JUVENILE WAY
OF DOING IT.

00:10:27.730 --> 00:10:30.560
Alda:
GEORGIA'S SELFISHNESS
HAS OTHER CONSEQUENCES.

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:32.160
INDIVIDUALS
SUCH AS GEORGIA

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:33.830
WHO ARE NOT VERY GENEROUS--

00:10:33.830 --> 00:10:35.630
WHEN THEY ARE IN NEED OF FOOD

00:10:35.630 --> 00:10:37.960
THEY ARE REJECTED
BY OTHER INDIVIDUALS

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:40.260
AS IF THE OTHER INDIVIDUALS
ARE SAYING

00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.430
"WELL, YOU'RE NEVER
SHARING WITH ME

00:10:42.430 --> 00:10:44.260
WHY SHOULD I SHARE WITH YOU?"

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:47.300
AND THIS IS ALSO HOW
YOUNG FEMALES SUCH AS GEORGIA

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:48.730
ARE GRADUALLY LEARNING

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:50.560
IT IS MUCH BETTER TO COOPERATE

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:52.060
WITH A SYSTEM
LIKE THAT.

00:10:52.060 --> 00:10:54.200
WE GET ACTUALLY MORE OUT OF IT

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:57.000
BY COOPERATING
AND CONTRIBUTING TO IT.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.360
Alda:
FRANS AND HIS RESEARCH ASSISTANT
MIKE SERES HAVE KEPT TRACK

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:03.860
IN THE THOUSANDS
OF TRIALS THEY HAVE RUN

00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:05.660
OF JUST WHO SHARES WITH WHOM.

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:08.930
WHAT'S REMARKABLE IS THAT
THE CHIMPS KEEP TRACK, TOO.

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:12.330
SO IF ONE CHIMP SHARES FOOD
WITH ANOTHER IN THE MORNING

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:13.960
THE GENEROSITY IS RETURNED

00:11:13.960 --> 00:11:17.730
BY A SPELL OF GROOMING
IN THE AFTERNOON.

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:34.960
THE VERY YOUNG ARE ALLOWED
TO GET AWAY WITH BEHAVIOR

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:36.830
THAT THE FEMALES IN THIS GROUP

00:11:36.830 --> 00:11:39.230
DON'T TOLERATE FROM
AN ADOLESCENT MALE.

00:11:41.730 --> 00:11:44.900
HE PICKS UP A STICK
AND TRIES INTIMIDATION

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:47.230
BUT THE GROUP ISN'T IMPRESSED.

00:11:52.060 --> 00:11:55.230
HERE'S GEORGIA,
AGAIN CAUSING TROUBLE.

00:11:55.230 --> 00:11:57.760
JIMOH AMBLES OVER,
NUDGES HER GENTLY

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:00.460
AND SHE HOLDS OUT HER HAND
IN APOLOGY.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:08.460
AGAIN, JIMOH BREAKS UP
A SQUABBLE.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:13.100
SO WHILE AS IN HUMAN SOCIETY,
THERE'S CONFLICT AND AGGRESSION

00:12:13.100 --> 00:12:16.130
CHIMPS HAVE MANY STRATEGIES
FOR KEEPING THE PEACE.

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:17.860
FRANS SEES IN THESE BEHAVIORS

00:12:17.860 --> 00:12:20.560
THE ROOT OF WHAT IN HUMANS
WE CALL MORALITY.

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:24.600
THEY HAVE MANY OF THE EMOTIONS
AND ELEMENTS OF HUMAN MORALITY

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:27.030
SUCH AS EMPATHY
AND SYMPATHY PROBABLY

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:31.030
GENEROSITY, CERTAIN FORMS OF
